entry.title: [Extensions c2s] Add ToolbarChipButton with flat edges
entry.content:
ToolbarButton has two formats: default and highlight (label with

border). This CL introduces a new formatting that allows the button

to have a flat edge. To not interfere with the existing toolbar

buttons formatting, it's implemented as ToolbarChipButton.



Toolbar chip button is used in the extensions toolbar to display

the extensions request access button (right flat edge) and the

extensions toolbar button (left flat edge only when request access

button is visible). This will allow us to remove the extensions

controls view and add the toolbar buttons directly to the extensions

container.

entry.title: Better test coverage for AutofillSyncMetadataTable
entry.content:
AutofillSyncMetadataTable is used to store sync metadata for all

components/autofill-related syncer::ModelTypes. The unit tests are

parameterized by ModelType. Since the list of relevant ModelTypes is

currently hardcoded, the tests are only run for two of the many

Autofill-related ModelTypes.



This CL runs the tests for all ModelTypes, by:

- Making the existing SupportsMetadataForModelType() public static.

- Using testing::ValuesIn() instead of testing::Values() and computing

the set of relevant ModelTypes as a function of

SupportsMetadataForModelType().



(Realistically speaking, since the logic is ModelType agnostic, it

doesn't really make a difference. But it's weird that the tests are

only run for two of the many types)

entry.title: Tweak NoStatePrefetch's pageVisibilityState
entry.content:
Before this CL, kHiddenButPainting is used in two cases:



1. to capture hidden tabs. These pages are treated as

a visible pages, such as media player.

2. NoStatePrefetch. This page lives in an invisible WebContents that

users are not aware of, so it should not be treated as a visible

page. It has a dedicated state because its previous version, legacy

prerender, needs to distinguish its frame's visible states from an

invisible frame. But now, we'd never render a NSP page, so it is

no longer needed.

(NSP is about to be replace by the new prerender2, but some

embedders are still relying on it.)



The case 2 is much closer to a kHidden page instead of a

kHiddenButPainting page, and should not be treated as a visible pages

as case 1.

So, this CL makes NSP use kHidden instead.



(Another option is to introduce another state, but after auditing all

callers, no one needs to know this state. Turing to "kHidden" also

allows us to remove the corresponding content/ public method.)



It also changes code that refers to this type, and turns to switch

instead of if to ensure they are aware of the exact types, in case

that we will introduce more states.

entry.title: Redistribute CSS properties between BoxData and SurroundData.
entry.content:
Struct fields for CSS properties are manually grouped into sub-structs,

with the hope that most property sets will touch just a few subgroups,

enabling efficient copy-on-write. However, this grouping is not

necessarily optimal and can be improved on using statistics. This patch

took the following approach:



1. Dump the Alexa1k test set (common top-level pages with DOM/style).

2. Compute style for every element, filtering out only properties that

fall into the âboxâ or âsurroundâ groups (this yields about 336k

sets of property names).

3. Group identical sets of properties, and keep only the 100

most common sets (this accounts for roughly 61% of the cases).

4. Ask the Z3 SMT solver to divide those properties into two distinct

sets, such that the total amount of RAM used for those 100 cases

(weighted by frequency) is as small as possible.



This gave these new groups, with properties moved marked with an

asterisk:



Box: border-style*, border-width*, margin*, padding*,

min-width/-height, max-width/-height, width, height, z-index



Surround: border-image, border-color, border-radius,

left/right/top/bottom, vertical-align,

aspect-ratio*, contain-intrinsic-width/-height*



In other words, the primary effect is to move a fair number of common

properties from âsurroundâ into âboxâ. (Surround is more than 300 bytes

large, so activating it less often is beneficial.) Some properties that

were never used, such as baseline-source, were just left alone since

they did not appear to make a large difference.



This gave a reasonable RAM improvement on our test set (measured by

the new BlinkStyleComputedStyleUsed metric; GCAllocated gives very

similar numbers):



Video 984 â 912 kB ( -72 kB)

Extension 4024 â 4031 kB ( +7 kB)

News 2074 â 1983 kB ( -91 kB)

ECommerce 301 â 269 kB ( -32 kB)

Social1 919 â 878 kB ( -41 kB)

Social2 638 â 637 kB ( -1 kB)

Encyclopedia 2144 â 2009 kB (-135 kB)

Sports 676 â 639 kB ( -37 kB)

Search 517 â 489 kB ( -28 kB)



The box/surround groups where chosen for this experiment due preliminary

analysis of the same data set showing that they were frequently activated

together.



It is likely possible to improve on this algorithm with some sort of

clever clustering algorithm (in particular, the algorithm does not seem

to scale well to doing _all_ property groups). We tried some variations

like using top-250 instead of top-100 (which makes the SMT solver

incapable of running to optimality within a reasonable amount of time),

or using three groups instead of two (including one nested in the

other), without clear improvements.



Even though the algorithm optimizes for memory used and not number

of allocations (which would probably favor more skewed group sizes),

it seemingly also gets a small performance gain. Style perftest, Zen 3,

LTO but no PGO:

entry.content:
Previously: While running a job, SyncSchedulerImpl computed whether

last_poll_reset_ was longer ago than the poll interval.



Now: SyncSchedulerImpl instead just checks whether the poll timer is

running - if it isn't, that means a poll is pending.



This removes a bit of logic, and it'll make the eventual switch from

OneShotTimer to WallClockTimer a bit easier.



Out of an abundance of caution, this change is behind a

(default-enabled) kill switch.

entry.title: Split AutofillSyncMetadataTable from AutofillTable
entry.content:
See go/splitting-autofill-table. All syncing logic in

components/autofill uses AutofillTable as its SyncMetadataStore. Since

the table is being split into autocomplete, payments and address related

functionality, the sync metadata store related logic is moved into a

separate table as well.



This CL creates a AutofillSyncMetadataTable WebDatabaseTable and moves

all relevant code + tests from AutofillTable there. The code is moved

1:1 without changes.

Like AutofillTable, it can be accessed through the a static

FromWebDatabase() getter. All users (i.e. all the sync bridges) are

updated accordingly.



Since payments sync uses both the Chrome profile scoped and the signed-

in account scoped database, the AutofillSyncMetadataTable exists in both

databases as well.

entry.title: [iOS] Clarify which password stores are profile store
entry.content:
Passwords have two stores, account and profile.

It used to have a single one, which was then renamed to Profile Store.

Many methods that used last year do not specify which store they use.

This CL rename some of those functions and clarifies their comment.



This is especially noticeable in the cases where the same function

existed for the account store, since there was a function whose

name stated "forAccount" and the other one did not clarify anything.



This has been done by recursively looking at methods, the method they

called referring to a store, and the method which called them, and

applying search and replace globally on those method names.



It is likely that I missed some methods.



This CL does not change the name of tests. It is not straightforward

which tests have been updated, which tests should be updated, which

tests should only work with the profile model.

entry.title: Fix use after free in XRWebGLLayer
entry.content:
When the antialias attribute is called on an inline session it echoes

the antialias value of the WebGL context's drawing buffer. If the WebGL

context has been lost, however, the drawing buffer is null.



This change checks to see if the context is lost before accessing the

drawing buffer. If so it returns false. This is a reasonable value

according to the spec, which states the attribute should return "false

if no antialiasing will be performed."

entry.title: [Win]update overlay swap chain size for power saving on battery mode
entry.content:
1. On battery-power mode, set swap chain size to the source content size

when the swap chain presents upscaled overlay, which is more power

saving (about 1% power saving on Alder Lake and 1.5% power saving on

Raptor Lake with resolution 1280X720 upscaled to 1920x1080) as the video

processor can do the minimal amount of work and the overlay has to read

the minimal amount of data.



2. For letterboxing feature, Optimize the calculation of dest_size/target_rect, and horizontal/vertical shifting.
